# Angular Guidelines

Angular is a platform and framework for building single-page client applications using HTML and TypeScript. The purpose of these guidelines is to provide consistency and best practices for Angular development within this project.

### Official Angular good practices

These are an excerpt of the official Angular guidelines you can find at [https://angular.dev/ai/develop-with-ai#custom-prompts-and-system-instructions](https://angular.dev/ai/develop-with-ai#custom-prompts-and-system-instructions).

We have only taken a subset that is compliant with our guidelines and at the same time compatible with Angular 16.

- Implement lazy loading for feature routes.
- Always use standalone components over NgModules.
- Set `changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush` in `@Component` decorator.
- Do NOT use the `@HostBinding` and `@HostListener` decorators. Put host bindings inside the `host` object of the `@Component` or `@Directive` decorator instead.
- Keep components small and focused on a single responsibility.
- Keep templates simple and avoid complex logic.
- Use the async pipe to handle observables.
- Prefer Reactive forms instead of Template-driven ones.
- Do NOT use `ngClass`, use `class` bindings instead.
- Do NOT use `ngStyle`, use `style` bindings instead.
- Use `NgOptimizedImage` for all static images and remember that it does not work for inline base64 images.
- Use `signal()` for local componente state management with `computed()` for derived state.
- Keep state transformations pure and predictable.
- Do NOT use `mutate` on signals, use `update` or `set` instead.
- Design services around a single responsibility and use the `providedIn: 'root'` option for singleton ones, so for most of the them in the project.
- Use the `inject()` function instead of constructor injection.

